\
4. \'91Desires, wishes, loves,\'92 literally, \'91hearts.\'92\
\
5. \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  signifies \'91salute,\'92 as in Chapter 12, 1, and 14, 1, and\
\uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 , \u8258 \u8258  (with various other forms) the \'91saluter,\'92 is the\
name of the Ape who is seen in the vignettes of the papyri saluting the\
rising of the sun. See M. Naville\'92s _Todtenbuch_, I, plates 21 and 22;\
the Papyrus of Ani, plate 2; the _Todtenbuch_ of Lepsius, Chapters 16\
and 126.\
\
I do not know how far it is correct to illustrate this undoubted origin\
of the Egyptian name for the Ape, as \'91the saluting one,\'92 by the\
following extract of a letter to Cuvier from M. Duvaucelle, about the\
Siamang apes in the neighbourhood of Bencoolen in Sumatra. \'93They\
assemble in numerous troops ... and thus united, they salute the rising\
and the setting sun with the most terrific cries, which may be heard at\
the distance of many miles; and which, when near, stun, when they do not\
frighten. This is the morning call of the mountain Malays, but to the\
inhabitants of the town, who are unaccustomed to it, it is a most\
insupportable annoyance.\'94\
\
In this place of the Book of the Dead the sign \uc0\u8258  is a mere\
determinative of the sound _a\uc0\u257 n_ with the notion of _salutation_, just\
as the sign \uc0\u8258  is a determinative of the sound _\u551 b_ with the notion of\
_thirst_.\
\
The \'91saluters\'92 of the rising sun are neither real apes nor men but the\
\'93Spirits of the East\'94 who, as we are told in an inscription of the tomb\
of Rameses VI, \'93effect the rising of R\'e2 by opening the door at each of\
the four portals of the eastern horizon of heaven. They it is who light\
him on both sides, and go forth in advance of him.... And when he arises\
they turn into six cynocephali.\'94[10]\
\
The Egyptian words in the later texts are \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \
\uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  the alternative reading being\
itself a proof that the difficulty of the text was already felt by some\
Egyptian scribe.\
\
But if the scribe had consulted the oldest texts accessible in his day,\
he would probably have seen another way out. Our oldest MS., that of\
Nebseni, reads, \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \
_bes-ku\uc0\u551  \u551 bu \u551 \u257 \u257 (n)u_, which signify literally, \'93antecedunt me corda\
salutantium.\'94 The word \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  _bes_ is a very common one in\
pictures representing the introduction of a king or a god into a temple.\
It is the technical term used in the Tablet of Canopus for the\
inducting, by the king, of priests into their offices. The subject of\
this verb is \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  _hearts_; an independent word, instead of\
being the mere determinative of \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 . The object of the verb is\
the speaker\'97\uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \'97_ku\u551 _, \'91me,\'92 as the papyrus _Pa_ reads, like\
_Aa_. And it is easy to see how the later text, which is already found\
in _Ax_, has been corrupted out of the older.\
