are, like so many other gods, Solar appellatives. \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  _Hu_\
is the Nourisher, \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  _Sau_, \'91the Knowing One.\'92 The god is\
also called \'91the Seer\'92 \uc0\u8258 , \'91He who heareth\'92 \u8258 \u8258 . These names are\
not personifications of the senses but, as in all cases, appellatives\
expressing attributes.\
\
12. See Note 2 on Chapter 4.\
\
13. The Eye (\uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 ) being the Sun or Moon, the period of\
distress (\uc0\u8258 \u8258 ) is that of obscuration or eclipse, and the hairy net\
(\uc0\u8258 \u8258 ) which is removed is the shadow which passes for a time over\
the heavenly body.\
\
The explanation which M. Maspero has recently given (P.S.B.A. XIV, 314)\
of the word \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 , as connected with \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \
\'91health,\'92 receives confirmation from the scholia in the papyri,\
according to which Thoth not only delivered the Eye from the\
veil of darkness which oppressed it, but carried it off\
\uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  \'91in life, health and strength,\
without any damage.\'92\
\
14. Mehurit is explained in the ancient scholion as \'91the Eye,\'92 but it is\
really the Sky, from which the Sun is born daily. The sign of plurality\
after Mehurit (if it means anything) only indicates the daily succession\
of the skies whence R\'e2 is born.\
\
15. The \'91coffined One\'92 \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  is of course Osiris, as it is\
plainly stated in the later scholia, which further add that the \'91Seven\
glorious ones\'92 who follow the coffin, or, as they read it, \'93their Lord,\'94\
are to be sought in the constellation of \'91the Thigh in the northern\
sky,\'92 that is in the seven stars of the Great Bear.\
\
These stars never set, but are perpetually revolving round the Pole. It\
is therefore evidently with the Polar Star that we must identify the\
coffin of Osiris. The names of the Seven Glorious ones vary according to\
the different authorities. And these Stars themselves receive other\
mythical forms; that of the Seven Cows and their Bull is recorded in the\
148th chapter. Names like \'91the Red-eyed\'92 \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  or the\
\'91Red-haired\'92 cow \uc0\u8258 \u8258  seem to imply _double_ stars. The \'91Red-eyed\'92\
is said to abide in \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  \'91house of gauze\'92 (perhaps a cobweb).\
\
The papyri add the important note that the \'93day of Come thou hither\'94!\
represents the moment \'93when Osiris says to R\'e2, Come thou hither\'94! or, as\
some read, \'93Come thou to me.\'94 The speaker adds that he sees the meeting\
of the two gods in Amenta.\
\
16. \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258  possessor of completeness, integrity, hence\
\'91inviolate.\'92 This name is given to Osiris when restored to his first\
condition after having been dismembered and cut into pieces. The god is\
called _R\'e2-Tmu-Nebert\'92er_ in the great Harris papyrus, 15, 3.\
\
17. It is most probable that the Cat became the representative of the\
Sun because of the homonymy between the Egyptian name \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \
_m\uc0\u551 \u551 u_ of the animal and the attributive \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  _mau_, \'91shining\'92\
said of the Sun. But the Egyptian scribe gives a different etymological\
explanation. Sau said of R\'e2 \'93he is \uc0\u8258 \u8258  _ma\u551 u_ of what he hath\
made.\'94 \uc0\u8258 \u8258  may, like the Latin _exemplar_, be either the type or\
the prototype, the copy or the original. The creatures of R\'e2 were made\
after his likeness. Sanskrit literature, from the \'c7atapatha Brahmana\
down to the Vishnu Pur\'e2na, is full of similar etymologies. The Egyptians\
from the very first delighted in this play upon words.\
\
