\
                             CHAPTER CXII.\
\
         _Chapter whereby one knoweth the Powers of Pu._[(1.)]\
\
\
Oh thou of corpselike form who art in Chait and \'c2npit;(2.) thou goddess\
of the Net,(3.) who art in Pu; ye who preside over the untilled lands,\
ye stars and constellations(4.).... Know ye wherefore Pu hath been given\
to Horus?\
\
I know it if ye know it not.\
\
It was R\'e2 who gave it to him in amends of the blindness in his eye, in\
consequence of what R\'e2 said to Horus: \'93Let me look at what is happening\
in thine eye to-day,\'94 and he looked at it.\
\
R\'e2 said to Horus, \'93Look, pray, at that black swine.\'94\
\
He looked, and a grievous mishap afflicted his eye.\
\
Horus said to R\'e2, \'93Lo, my eye is as though the eye of Sutu had made a\
wound in my own eye.\'94 And wrath devoured his heart.\
\
And R\'e2 said to the gods, \'93Let him be laid upon his bed, that he may\
recover.\'94\
\
It was Sutu who had taken the form of a black swine, and he wrought the\
wound which was in the eye of Horus.\
\
And R\'e2 said to the gods, \'93The swine is an abomination to Horus; may he\
get well.\'94 And the swine became an abomination to Horus.(5.)\
\
And the circle of gods said, who were with him when Horus came to light\
in his own children:(6.) \'93Let the sacrificial victims(7.) for him be of\
his oxen, of his goats, and of his swine.\'94\
\
As for Emsta, Hapi, Tuamautef, Kebhsenuf, Horus is their father and Isis\
their mother.\
\
And Horus said to R\'e2, \'93Give me then two(8.) brothers in Pu and two\
brothers in Nechen, of this my own body; and that they may be with me as\
an everlasting renewal, through which the earth flourisheth and storms\
are quenched.\'94\
\
And his name became that of Horus upon his Column.\
\
I know the Powers of Pu: they are Horus, Emsta and Hapi.\
\
                                 NOTES.\
\
1. On the situation of _Pu_, see chapter 18, note 6. The Pyramid Texts\
(Pepi I, 684) speak of the \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258  \'93those of the\
Red Crown who are in Pu.\'94\
\
2. _Thou of corpselike form in Chait and \'c2npit._ The sign of the plural,\
here as elsewhere, is quite consistent with its application to a single\
person. \uc0\u8258 \u8258  _Chait_ is the name[95] of the 16th, or Mendesian,\
Nome of Northern Egypt, and \'c2npit was its metropolis. The nome is\
mentioned in the inscription of Amten in the third dynasty. The god is\
Osiris. He is invoked in the \'93Lamentations of Isis and Nephthys,\'94 and\
asked to come to Tattu, \'c2npit and Chait, which are but different names\
of one Sanctuary, _Cf._ Brugsch, _Zeitschr._, 1871, p. 81, and his\
translation of the Mendesian Tablet, _Zeitschr._, 1875.\
\
3. _Thou goddess of the Net_ \uc0\u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 \u8258 . This name\
corresponds to the Greek Diktynna. The reason why a goddess representing\
Heaven should be so called may be understood by the Homeric epithet\
\uc0\u960 
