cases generally, and on funereal tablets. Between the Eyes on many\
tablets we frequently find the sign \uc0\u8258 , and this is often followed by\
the sign of Water \uc0\u8258  or the Vase \u8258 , and very frequently by both.\
Very often we have two signs \uc0\u8258 , one by each Eye, and not less\
frequently a pair of jackals, \uc0\u8258  or \u8258  facing each other. No two\
tablets are exactly alike, but the meaning is always the same.\
\
Nor is the meaning changed when the tablet is headed by the Winged Disk\
\uc0\u8258  or \u8258  even though the Eyes are not seen. Their place is\
supplied by two Ur\'e6i, sometimes crowned with the \uc0\u8258  and the \u8258 ,\
insignia of Southern and Northern sovereignty.\
\
On a fine tablet of the twelfth dynasty (_Denkm._, II, 136_b_), the sign\
\uc0\u8258  is attached to each Ur\'e6us, and this device is repeated on\
innumerable monuments.\
\
According to another device the Two Eyes are represented within the\
Winged Disk (see _e.g._, Leemans, _Mon._, III, _M._, Pl. XVI).\
\
\'93He of the Pair of Eyes\'94 is always Osiris. But Osiris is a god \'93of many\
